Title: move MRE logic out of batch file
Body: Batch files are not portable.  Makefiles are portable.    Whenever humanly possible  PLEASE put logic (especially defaults) in makefiles  not custom build scripts.  The "as-is" meant that when I build on Linux  my MRE boots with the wrong default config.  This fixes that by putting sensible defaults in the makefiles  where any copy of make can figure out what to do.

Title: Template ize bin value length for interpolation
Body: Switch `interpolate2d` to use a template parameter for the `size` argument.  Since it's known at compile time  we can use the compiler to make guarantees about the things we're passing in.    This allows for the following:  1) `bins` and `values` must be arrays - not bare pointers  1) The length of the `bins` and `values` arrays must match  2) You can't pass in a length that isn't correct for the bins/values you've passed in (buffer overrun is difficult or impossible).  The compiler will deduce the correct `TSize` value by the arrays that are passed in.    I have some more changes coming that will further leverage this  and clean up table consumption  so we don't have to pass bins/values/name every time.

Title: Store table ratio at compile time
Body: Since the ratio from stored value to "real" value in a table can't change at runtime  we should store and compute it all at compile time.  This change uses `std::ratio` to embed the ratio in the type  instead of expecting consumers to remember to use it.    Also moves implementation up in to the declaration  to prevent having to re-write the full templated type every single time (see old file  line 110 for an example).

Title: cisnan warnings fix
Body: We use a bit of C++ magic to fix tons of these warnings:  ```      util/efilib.h:48:35: warning: dereferencing type-punned pointer will break strict-aliasing rules [-Wstrict-aliasing]      #define cisnan(f) (*(((int*) (&f))) == 0x7FC00000)                                     ^      controllers/error_handling.h:54:59: note: in definition of macro 'efiAssertVoid'  ```  Due to the gnu-c++ optimisation  the binary code produced is practically the same as before:  ```        87               @ aliasing-test.cpp:15:  if (cisnan(oneDegreeUs)) {        88 0010 20309FE5   ldr r3  .L6+4 @ tmp118         89 0014 030050E1   cmp r0  r3 @  tmp118        90 0018 0200000A   beq .L5 @   ```  But without optimisation it's slightly larger (by 2-3 opcodes)  so we leave it as it was for -O0...

Title: Performance improvement call GetBaseFuel less
Body: As shown in #973  both `MainTriggerCallback` and `PeriodicFastCallback` call `GetInjectionDuration`  updating the stored injection duration in the engine state.    The trigger callback calls it for every tooth we actually use (generally all rising or all falling edges).  `GetInjectionDuration` takes about 32us to execute  incurring a 32us cost in every tooth decode interrupt.  On high tooth count triggers  this one call can incur significant CPU cost.  For example  on a 60-2 wheel  it's called 5800 times per second  which amounts to 19% of total CPU load on an STM32F4 at 168MHz.    This change omits the call from MainTriggerCallback  and increases the frequency of the `PeriodicFastCallback` to 200hz to make up for the removal.  Since `PeriodicFastCallback` takes around 100us  this will use a constant 2% CPU (up from 0.5% for PFC previously  plus a variable amount from MainTriggerCallback).    All of the calls made to the various acceleration enrichment algorithms made by `getInjectionDuration` are idempotent  so it's safe to call them whenever without changing the result.  Important state is updated only as needed from the trigger callbacks.

Title: Simplify thermistor config

Title: low hanging performance fruit
Body: We only need to do the cache invalidation if we're actually about to read them  which means we should only do it on complete  not half done.  Same goes for updating ADC subscribers.

Title: Sensors composition inheritance
Body: Since converted sensors just use some function [float] -> [SensorResult]  compose the sensor out of a function to separate concerns of being a sensor  and converting sensor readings.  This is implemented via templates so that assembly of the sensor occurs at compile time  incurring zero runtime overhead (probably actually an improvement  since a virtual method lookup is no longer involved).    This also opens the possibility for more complex sensor types to use compositions of functions  such as a fuel level sensor that converts volts -> resistance -> liters  using for example a `VoltageDividerConverter` and a `TableLookupConverter` chained together.

Title: add sensor framework tests
Body: Add new sensor framework  plus unit tests.  ~~Not currently consumed anywhere - so no actual function changes to the firmware yet.~~ **Oil pressure sensor logic replaced as a first consumer!**    Features:  - Uniform consumption of sensors  including failure detection  - `SensorReader<T>` provides simple sensor consumption including fallback logic  - Transparent sensor mocking both in tests and at runtime  including via the console  - Sensor results are only computed when new ADC values are read  and cached for later consumption (prevents doing extra work converting the sensor every time)  - Reduces code duplication by decoupling _how_ to convert a sensor from _what_ we're sensing.  Not only does this simplify the code  it reduces the byte size of hot code  putting less stress on the instruction cache and branch predictor.  - Provides framework for sensor redundancy/fallback/compositing: a sensor implementation can read other sensors  and decide what to return based on their values (example: TPS sensor redundancy)  - Adding new sensors is cheap and easy - see comment in `sensor.h`  - Separates implementation from initialization: sensors are implemented in `controllers/sensors/`  and wired up in `init/sensors/`.  This makes it easy to test functionality in an isolated test world.

Title: Fix mystery 400ns 1us pulse at MCU startup

This manifested as (and was discovered by) ignition outputs giving a 400ns-1us blip as they were initialized.  This change prevents any such blips from occurring by setting the state of the pin before we actually enable it  so it will immediately do the right thing.

Also  chopping down to 0.2 volt increments loses so much resolution that MAF wouldn't actually work very well.  - `getMafVoltage` now gets the voltage at the maf pin  - `getRealMaf` gets the mass flow rate  in kg/hr (TODO: should we do kg/s or g/s instead?    This change makes a negligible change to compiled image size  but saves 1KB (!) of RAM.

Title: Coasting Fuel Cut Fixes
Body: This PR solves two problems:  1) When fuel is cut  getInjectionDuration returns zero duration  so that no fuel is injected (as desired).  However  when handleFuelInjectionEvent goes to schedule the opening and closing of the injectors schedules two events very close together (sometimes exactly on top of each other).  These events sometimes get swapped in order of execution by the scheduler  so the injector will STICK OPEN FLOODING THE ENGINE.  I discovered this when driving  and the coasting fuel cut caused my O2 sensors to read full scale rich.    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/41796404-0588b58a-762c-11e8-9f5b-851014437467.png)    Here's an example of that condition while running on the bench.  Note that it sometimes sticks open  and sometimes doesn't because it's a tossup between whether the opening or closing event gets scheduled first.    This fix for this problem adds a check in handleFuelInjectionEvent to skip scheduling injections with very small (< 50us) duration.    2) An additional check is added for a maximum MAP pressure at which fuel is cut during coasting.  On my car the first ~3 percent of the throttle travel does quite a bit  so a threshold for manifold pressure is required so that fuel isn't cut under light throttle  only when actually coasting.  This also provides flexibility so that a throttle position sensor isn't strictly required to use the feature.    ps: Andrey check your email for my signed contributor agreement

Title: Fix accel enrichment for negative fuel pulse
Body: If the target fuel was very small  and there was lots of fuel on the wall  you could get an injector pulse of <0.  This will inject no fuel (like a pulse of 0ms would)  but will more importantly screw up the estimate for how much fuel is on the wall.  If the pulse went negative  the model would update as though the injector had sucked fuel back in to the tank.

Required a dedicated hardware timer  but now only relies on core OS functionality to run the ADC.    This closes #630.

Title: Make stacks smaller
Body: Excerpt from `ChibiOS/os/common/ports/ARMCMx/chcore_v6m.h`:  ```  /**   * @brief   Per-thread stack overhead for interrupts servicing.   * @details This constant is used in the calculation of the correct working   *          area size.   * @note    In this port this value is conservatively set to 64 because the   *          function @p chSchDoReschedule() can have a stack frame  especially   *          with compiler optimizations disabled. The value can be reduced   *          when compiler optimizations are enabled.   */  #if !defined(PORT_INT_REQUIRED_STACK)  #define PORT_INT_REQUIRED_STACK         64  #endif  ```    Interrupts are NOT serviced on the stack of the thread that was running when the interrupt occurred.  The only thing that happens on that thread's stack is that its registers are pushed (by hardware) when an interrupt occurs  just before swapping the stack pointer out for the main stack (currently 0x400=1024 bytes)  where the ISR actually runs.    Likewise  the idle thread actually doesn't do anything  so it shouldn't be so tremendous.    This change saves a lot of RAM.  640 bytes per thread + 960 for the idle thread.

Title: simplify dequeue logic
Body: For some reason  dequeuing events from our scheduler queue was a two phase process:  1) move all events that are due to run to their own temporary list  2) execute everything in that list.    I can't come up with a good reason for why we were doing that.    This change simply pops elements off the head one at a time  and executes them  instead of the aforementioned complicated (and slow) logic.    Unit tests pass  but pending testing on real hardware.

Body: - Implement `scaled_channel` which allows a scaled output channel (for example  storing quarter-RPM) to be used as though it was a normal float  even though it's backed by a different type.  - Reorder TS output channels in roughly reverse priority order.  Since rarely used channels are at the end  datalogging can be sped up by reading a contiguous block of channels near the beginning that we actually care about (for example  logging up thru `lastErrorCode`  140 bytes  updates at 210-215hz while datalogging on a debug build on an stm32f4 over USB.  This previously ran at ~90hz).  - This change reduces total output channel size from 356 to 220 bytes    The modifications to `tle8888.h`/`c` were required because that `tunerstudio_configuration.h` now requires c++  so we inject only the debug channels where we need them in c-land.    This change has been tested by both @960 and myself.  I adjusted tune settings where possible to test channels  and where not possible to test on the bench  I modified the function in `status_loop.cpp` to manually set values  then confirm that they showed as expected in TS.

Title: Re shrink stacks
Body: Finally got a break in to the debugger under the hardware-in-the-loop test conditions that tripped the stack warning.    The problem is that the servo thread directly calls `scheduleForLater`  which could end up executing events off of the queue.  If the ECU is in self-stimulation mode  one of those events could be firing an emulated trigger event  which could then call a relatively deep call hierarchy (`mainTriggerCallback`  etc) that normally runs on the giant (4k) interrupt stack.    Inspection of the caller tree for `doExecute` reveals that the servo is the only time we do this.  Every other call to `doExecute` is made from an interrupt context.    The short term solution is to simply make that one stack big  instead of all stacks. Longer term solution is to do something different for servo control (if we need servo control at all...?)  or re-engineer how we do scheduling for events scheduled in the very near future (that we may miss if we set the timer).

Title: Inject timestamps in to hwHandleShaftSignal
Body: Taking the timestamp long after the interrupt has occurred gives an opportunity for not only a fixed offset error (time elapses between interrupt and timestamp)  but also jitter.  The more time that elapses without taking the timestamp  the more time other interrupts could occur (or even different execution time due to branches).    The next work is to inject this timestamp all the way down to listeners - most importantly the logic that schedules ignition events  so that ignition timing is referenced to the actual trigger tooth event  not the trigger tooth event plus however long some logic takes to run (source of both offset error and jitter!).

Title: Require tooth reference time for scheduleByAngle

Title: Pass action_s instead of callback param

It doesn't make sense to be able to pass one along without the other  so this change glues them together.    This also lets us do nice stuff like define a constructor that takes a callback but no parameter  without having to explicitly mention that we want to pass null.    Tangentially related to #1080 and #974 as it will make some refactoring for scheduling a batch of events simpler.    _note_: Since we're passing by value  this change probably doesn't actually change the generated code.  Instead of passing a pair of pointers  we now pass a struct that contains two pointers.

Title: move flash addr in to mpu_util

Title: Closed loop controller base ETB testing
Body: - Controller base frames out the structure of a basic open loop + closed loop controller.  Implementing a new controller only requires implementing the five virtual functions of the base.  These functions are often each very simple.  Each can return `unexpected` to indicate a failure has occured  which will be passed to the final one so it can put the system in a safe state.      - `getSetpoint`: where is the controller trying to move the plant?      - `observePlant`: where is the plant now? (this means read a sensor  usually)      - `getOpenLoop`: get any output value that should occur as a function of only the setpoint.      - `getClosedLoop`: get any output value that should occur as a function of the setpoint and observed state      - `setOutput`: drive whatever output system this controller drives  making an adjustment to the plant in the physical world  - Consume new controller base with ETB  - Thorough tests for controller base  - First ETB test against new controller base: checking whether we're reading the correct TPS sensor based on the ETB's index  - Update gtest: required for the new and improved `MOCK_METHOD` macro

Improve ETB idle control
Body: Here's the problem.  With ETB idle configured  it currently just scoots the whole target position up by the desired idle amount.  If your pedal target table has values of 0-100% in it  that means you can now try to move the throttle to [0 + idle  100 + idle]  which probably isn't what you wanted.     This change moves the "virtual 0% position" to be at the idle position  and leaves 100% as-is.  That means at 50% target  the actual position target will be 50% + idle/2.

Title: remove warning message in tune
Body: This was causing several issues:  - Every time the ECU reboots  TunerStudio has to do a full read of the configuration (20KB)  because the CRC will never match.  If a warning fired in either the previous boot or the current one  the tune (and corresponding CRC) won't match  so it'll have to re-read from the ECU.  This takes ~20 seconds over 115k baud UART  and even longer over Bluetooth  which is not acceptable.  - When TS sends a burn command to the ECU  it then immediately checks the CRC to ensure that the write was successful  and the controller's state matches its internal state.  If a warning has fired since the last full read of the ECU  TS's internal state is now inconsistent with that in the controller  so the CRC check will fail  and TS will display this error message:  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/80036757-344ba900-84a7-11ea-8bdf-d7d3b3bd267a.png)    Many users (myself included) have been concerned that the display of this message indicated that something went wrong (which technically  it had)  when in fact the burn had succeeded fine  but the ECU had changed part of the tune (the warning message) unbeknownst to TunerStudio.

Title: don t store microsecond timer callback with a pointer
Body: We were using a function pointer here  when the target never changes.  This is what the linker was designed for.  A side effect of using a func ptr is that the compiler can't inline across a function pointer call - it doesn't know where the call is going.  Using a normal function call allows it to generate far more optimal code.  Also  we don't have to do a null check now  because the "equivalent check" happens at compile time.

Title: General purpose PWM configuration fields
Body: Problem: While hugely flexible  FSIO is too complex for the average user. Users require an easy way to configure things that are relatively simple like:  - Vary fuel pump duty cycle with engine load  - Engage/disengage supercharger clutch  - PWM cooling fan control: increase duty as temperature increases  - Automatic transmission line pressure control  - Decrease windshield wiper speed with increasing engine load to emulate old vacuum operated wipers while trying to sneak an EFI'd classic in to a stingy Concours d'Elegance  - Light bulb marked `DANGER TO MANIFOLD` that gets brighter with increasing boost pressure    Solution: After a survey of other ECUs functionality  I came up with this.  I tried to strike a balance between both ease of use  and flexibility to support may different scenarios.  It supports:  - PWM duty lookup from a table  with selectable Y axis (extensible to more channels later)  - Selectable output frequency  - On-off mode with configurable rising/falling thresholds for easy to understand hysteresis  similar to existing fan control  - Fallback duty cycle in case of sensor or table lookup error    Here's what the config UI for one (of four) channels looks like:  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/80290786-b5e84480-86fc-11ea-8ce8-3eddc16f3c88.png)

Title: Move ETB control to a thread
Body: - Move ETB to its own thread  because:      - Auto TPS calibrate is greatly simplified by the use of `chThdSleep`      - Things running on a timer (instead of a thread) don't participate it the RTOS's thread priority system  and operate essentially "first come first serve"  which risks starvation.  Since ETB is a safety critical device  we need the hard RTOS guarantee that it will be scheduled over other less important tasks.  - Clean up ETB defaults  - Hard code ETB update speed.  Since this is a safety critical system with no real reason for a user to ever need to change the update rate  it's now locked to 500hz  along with the ADC.  The increase from 200 to 500 gives a considerable increase in loop bandwidth and responsiveness.

Title: TS protocol framing for auto tune calibration features
Body: In order for automatic tuning/calibration to provide a great experience  we need some way to exfiltrate data from the ECU back up to TunerStudio  and set it in the configuration.    Here's an example of how this works:  ```  maintainConstantValue = tpsMax  { (calibrationMode == 1 ) ? calibrationValue : tpsMax }  maintainConstantValue = tpsMin  { (calibrationMode == 2 ) ? calibrationValue : tpsMin }  ```  This line tells TunerStudio:  - when `calibrationMode == 1`  copy the value read in from `calibrationValue` to the configuration field `tpsMax`  - Otherwise just pipe `tpsMax` back in to itself (ie  do nothing)  ...and likewise for tpsMin  but for mode `2`.    With this simple construct  the ECU can send any number of internally computed configuration fields back to TunerStudio  getting around the problem of setting values on the controller without TS's knowledge.  The ECU simply has to sequentially set a mode/value  wait briefly  then repeat until all the values it wants to send have been sent.    This change adds the new fields `calibrationMode` and `calibrationValue`.  Because TS will always read these with the mere existence of `maintainConstantValue`  they have to be packed near the existing "important" fields  so as to not hurt update rate and datalogging speed.  As a result  everything after them has to get scooted up by 8 bytes.  In addition  the signature is revved to prevent incompatible protocol problems.

Title: Remove scheduler debug pins
Body: Setting an output pin incurs a cost of around 1 microsecond.  We were doing four sets/clears per scheduler queue event.  A V8 schedules around 60 events per cycle.  At 6000 rpm  that's 2800 events scheduled per second.  At a cost of four microseconds extra overhead per event  we were spending 1.1% of our CPU load  on an F4  changing the state of pins that are never actually configured.    In other terms  we can look at the overhead cost of scheduling one event.  The overhead for a single event (total interrupt time - actual work time) was 16.1us - but this change saves nearly 4  reducing overhead by 28%!

Title: Fix 100 duty injection
Body: If you hit 100% duty cycle  we used to skip every other injection  resulting in Major Misbehavior.    ~~This change makes the behavior a bit safer.  If we are operating with very high duty cycle (>95%)  don't bother closing the injectors at all. Pin them fully open  so you get everything your fuel system has to give  instead of half.~~    If duty cycle gets near 100%  we cut fuel (like a rev limit).  This is safer than trying to pin the injectors open at 100%  because it can't let you quietly go lean and melt a piston.    Fixes #1430.

Body: For things that are either:  - a bug  - a combination of config settings that will result in undefined or otherwise wrong behavior    We want to trip a fatal error  because there is no (automatic) corrective action the ECU can take to limp along.    The most common cases this covers are things like inconsistent configurations (ex: wrong firing order for cyl count)  and clearly invalid configurations (unexpected enum values).    This PR also makes calls to `firmwareError` in unit tests throw an exception (so the test registers as failed)  instead of simply calling `exit` which will terminate the process immediately.

Title: Update to Matt s MAF code for VE table tuning
Body: PR-ing this now in the spirit of small changes.   Built upon Matt's last PR to allow the MAF fuelling to be tuned with the VE table.   MAF air charge fuelling now targets AFR and has correction for air flow inconsistencies like reversion through the MAF.   Creates a value for "airChargeLoad" which is a standardised VE value and is used as Y axis for the VE table.   VE table tunes MAF fuel by percentage. 100 = no correction  80 = 20% less fuel  120 = 20% more fuel.   VE table enabled in Tuner studio for LM_REAL_MAF instead of Fuel Table.    Known issues:  Pulse width output is tested ok but does cause the build test to fail due to the change in the maths.  Y axis on VE table does not move in TS  need to change rusefi.input file to solve this for the next PR.   For now the table works but does not show a live highlight/cursor in TS.

Title: pwm perf
Body: This change avoids a conversion from float -> int64.  On 32bit ARM  this conversion has to be done in software  which takes around 2 microseconds!  On the other hand  conversion from float -> int32 is done in hardware  and only takes a single cycle (~6 nanoseconds).  The intermediate result doesn't need to be 64 bit.  The addition that happens in the return statement is ok because a 64b integer add only requires a second cycle over a 32 bit add  with no conversion step.

Title: simplify getTimeNowNt
Body: While working on #1874  I rewrote `getTimeNowNt` to be much simpler.  On ARM this implementation is actually branch free  so has the potential to be faster.    To answer the deleted comment ` // todo: why is this implementation not used? `:  In a real-time application  I think we prefer a deterministic algorithm  even if it requires a global lock.  A lock free solution has terrible worst case performance  which is what we care most about when realtime.  At -O2  we're only locked for something like 16-18 cycles - only 110 nanoseconds.  It's just not enough time to worry about.

Title: switch to single precision constants
Body: `0.25`: this is a double  `0.25f`: this is a float    Adding this compiler option means these are both actually floats.  We don't have the hardware to process doubles  so it happens instead in software.    For example  the line of code `float instantRpm = (60000000.0 / 360 * US_TO_NT_MULTIPLIER) * angleDiff / time;` compiles to this:    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/96042981-2017b180-0e23-11eb-911a-c9871357c2ac.png)    Circled are SOFTWARE EMULATED `double` math operations.  Bad! Slow! So much extra code!    With this option added  it now compiles to this:    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/96043358-afbd6000-0e23-11eb-8c31-ba4c5d7a995a.png)    As a bonus  this saves ~1k of flash space.

Title: Remove trigger listener list
Body: the trigger listener list is a double perf killer:  - it's a loop of runtime-determined length  so it can't be unrolled  - it's a loop of double indirect calls  so they can't be branch predicted or prefetched.  Removing the list and converting to direct calls means they can be inlined  which is good for everybody.

Title: convert mass duration later in the pipeline
Body: Convert to duration later in the fueling pipeline.  This means all corrections (cranking  CLT/IAT/duration  etc) are applied as a mass  not as a duration  with injector deadtime added at the very end  after all corrections.    As a side effect  this means the base cranking value is now a mass (milligrams)  not a duration (milliseconds)  so it's now automatically adjusted by the injector settings  and will soon be adjusted by the fuel pressure too  which will provide better startup performance for GDI  and potentially PFI even without a pump prime!    fixes #1903 by design  not with a hack like #1904 did

Title: unlock relock between scheduler queue events
Body: This might help with sync loss problems.  One potential issue is that a long sequence of timer events keep a lock held (by the scheduling queue)  so no trigger interrupts can happen while that sequence is being executed.  This change unlocks the global lock every iteration so that an interrupt can fire  then immediately re-locks.  This is safe to do because it is equivalent to the trigger interrupt being called by a scheduled event  which is something we already do in the form of trigger self stimulation.

Title: force a pwm cycle start skip cycles if late
Body: If we're far behind schedule on PWM  skip cycles to catch up instead of executing every single event we missed.      Trying to catch up will just swamp the scheduler while generating extremely high speed PWM (I measured it at ~50-70khz) that isn't actually doing anything useful.  For example  if you were trying to generate a 60-2 wheel at 6000 rpm  that's 12000 events per second  and if the flash erase + write takes 3 seconds  that leaves you with ~36k events to try and execute once the flash is done  which will be cranked out as fast as the PWM driver can toggle a pin.

Title: Fix gpio reinit race condition
Body: Bug: if you un-initialize a pin  setValue will still work! If you initialize pin A  then set it to "none"  then initialize the same pin elsewhere  both users will be able to call setValue and set the same pin!  This causes a problem in particular when reinitializing a pin that's set by a higher priority thread  like the hardware trigger emulator does.    This PR fixes both possibilities:  - Only do the hardware set if `brainPin != GPIO_UNASSIGNED`  which is now always set by `initPin`  and always cleared by `unregister`.  - Guard pin init and de-init with a critical section so that other threads couldn't even set the pin if they tried

Title: fix race condition in CommandQueue massively speeding up HW CI tests
Body: The pattern of   ```  send request  wait for response or timeout  ```  doesn't actually work  because if the "signal listening thread" action happens elsewhere prior to you starting to listen  you get stuck.  This had the effect of waiting for the timeout (10 seconds for `set engine_type`!) instead of the command actually completing!    This PR changes it to instead  ```  start listening for response  send request  wait for completion or timeout  ```  which means we actually return immediately upon confirmation of the command as intended.    It also removes the retry timeout  as any connectivity problem that requires a retry indicates a bug  and we should just fail hard so the issue can be diagnosed (besides  the retry mechanism was sort of broken anyway).

Title: Idle timing uses phase logic remove falloff
Body: - Refactor idle timing PID logic in to the idle controller class  using the phase determination logic to ensure idle timing and normal idle pid are engaged together. (this removes the need for independent "is idling" config fields for spark)  - Removes idle timing PID falloff based on falloff region both in RPM and TPS.  - ~Likewise  removes the deadzone for idle timing pid.~    The reasoning for the last two:  Falloff has issues because it reduces the effective gain of the controller when in the falloff region  which can encourage windup when the gain suddenly increases when it makes it in to the un-falloff'd region.    ~A deadzone causes the opposite problem where the engine speed changes  but the controller doesn't respond because it's still inside the deadzone.  Then suddenly the engine leaves the deadzone  the controller wakes up  but realizes it's been caught with its pants down because it did nothing to respond while inside the deadzone.  This hurts response because the controller *could* have responded while in the deadzone  but didn't.~ There is a reasonable case for deadzone  un-deleted!

implement bit banged I2C driver
Body: Implement a bit-banged I2C controller for low priority I2C operations.    Bit-banged (as opposed to hardware accelerated) provides several benefits:  - No interrupts required  - No usage of microcontroller resources (particularly DMA channels)  - No operating system locks (any other thread can preempt an operation)  - Smaller code size  - No restriction on pins: can use any two GPIO pins    progress on #2288 and #2281

Title: increase SD card speed
Body: SD spec says 0-25MHz for slow mode  and 0-50MHz for fast mode.    Increases slow mode to either 10.5MHz or 5.25MHz (depending on which SPI device it is)  and fast mode to 42MHz or 21MHz (depending on which SPI device it is).  On an F7 that means 13.5mhz/6.75mhz slow mode and 54MHz/27MHz fast mode  which is pushing it a little bit on SPI1  but will probably be just fine.

Title: Store ini filesystem in compressed block device
Body: This PR converts the ini filesystem from:  ini file -> zip file -> FAT filesystem (ini decompressed by pc)  to  ini file -> FAT filesystem -> gzip (entire filesystem decompressed on the fly  in-ECU)    This means that the filesystem appears to contain an ini file  not an ini.zip file.  With this  you can open the ini *directly from TunerStudio* instead of having to first unzip it to your PC.  As an added bonus  it consumes less flash space - currently about 75k  but presents as a full 1MB filesystem.    Unfortunately  right now it requires 32KB of RAM to store the DEFLATE dictionary  which means it doesn't fit on an F405/7 (but does fit on an F42x/F7/H7).  It may be possible to compress with a smaller dictionary  but I haven't tried yet.

Title: Embed ini

Title: Extract slow adc
Body: Always sample all slow ADC channels (this will allow changing ADC input mappings at runtime  which is currently impossible!)    This doesn't really hurt performance  as the vast majority of the time spent in the function `readSlowAnalogInputs` is spent with the thread asleep and the ADC converting samples on its own  copying to RAM via DMA.    As a bonus this saves a little memory since now the slow ADC's config group can live in flash  instead of RAM  as it's a constant.

Title: rewrite text logging system
Body: No longer require a logging buffer for every thread that needs one.  Instead  use a queue of buffers so one thread can't block execution (particularly of interrupts!) when it writes to the log.    Uses ChibiOS message queues to maintain one queue of free buffers  and one queue of used buffers.  When a thread wants to write  it acquires a free buffer  prints to it  and pushes it in to the used queue.  A dedicated thread then dequeues and writes lines from the used buffer in to the large output buffer.    probably fixes #884 too    fixes #2524

Title: send voltage and heater enable to WBO controller
Body: ECU knows battery voltage and when to enable heater  send those over CAN.  We can do better heater control with supply voltage info  and better warmup behavior if the ECU can tell the WBO controller when to start heating (ie  after engine start plus some delay)    Also updates wideband firmware itself to read that CAN message and automatically compensate for supply voltage in the heater control.

Title: Start on HSI clock
Body: use HSI for startup so that:    - we do initialization at full clock speed  not a fraction of it on crystals other than 25MHz  - Prevent possible boot failures due to out-of-spec input to PLL.  With 25Mhz crystal  we got 1MHz input  but any smaller crystal would be below the minimum allowed input frequency of 0.95 MHz.    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/125418909-7cc0dea4-0675-464b-9fba-24752b995c06.png)

hotfix 2944 broken icon paths in rusefi_autoupdate
Body: The problem was that none classloader of rusefi_autoupdate contains the path to `rusefi_console.jar` and URLClassLoader which is used to load `rusefi_console.jar` didn't embed in the classloaders hierarchy. Nevertheless  to load icons you use `getResource()` from `Class` this method just resolves resource name according to class package and consequently use its ClassLoader `getResource()` method. Eventually  the path to the `rusefi_console.jar` keeps nowhere after invoking the `Launcher.main` method. Thus  to solve this problem we should someway insert the path for `rusefi_console.jar`.    Solutions:  1. Insert jar's URL to system classloader using Reflection API  2. Embed classloader with jar's URL to the classloaders hierarchy. __Maybe impossible__  3. Use only our custom classloader with jar's URL to load icons. __Used in branch__    'Cause the `AutoupdateUtil.class.getResource()` was removing the leading slashes and I had no idea where these paths with slashes come from  I had to emulate this logic in my classloader.

Title: don t validate instant RPM
Body: Not much reason to do this - we don't make this check at all for non-instant RPM  so there isn't a reason to do it for instant RPM either.  It could actually hinder starting for an engine that starts quickly - it will give a wrong RPM reading if the engine kicks before a full cycle has completed  increasing engine speed past the cranking threshold before a full cycle (and "normal" RPM reading) is complete.  The wrong RPM will cause events to be scheduled late  possibly hindering engine start  as it means ignition timing will be (possibly significantly) retarded from the set value.

Title: overdwell protection
Body: Prevents overdwell by always scheduling the coil fire  then canceling it later when we get more precise information.    This snip shows the engine sniffer with a hack installed to skip scheduling of every 10th spark firing schedule event.  The two dwells with arrows are 50% longer  since they were fired by overdwell protect  instead of by normal spark scheduling.    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/132112446-8973ac57-4a26-4a3d-8f95-655fdb388019.png)    Without this change  those two coils would hang open  possibly melting the coil  to be eventually fired on the next engine cycle.    fix #3071 and probably #3196 too

Title: reduce updateTunerStudioState stack usage
Body: `updateTunerStudioState` uses a ton of stack on unoptimized builds  since it doesn't reuse stack space for multiple different locals/scratch work unless you enable optimization.  It will  however  reuse the same stack space if the work is being done by different functions!    When optimization is enabled  this change has almost no impact - all these new functions get inlined  and the stack space reused so very little is used in that case either way.    helps #3302

Title: DRAFT Fix cranking idling taper phase for useSeparate ForIdle tables
Body: Currently useSeparateAdvanceForIdle and useSeparateVeForIdle are broken because of https://github.com/rusefi/rusefi/pull/2900    We fix it by changing the isIdling() method's behavior. This method is used only by useSeparateAdvanceForIdle & useSeparateVeForIdle. And it doesn't know about "CrankToRunTaper" phase. The solution is that CrankToRunTaper should be actually CrankToIdleTaper  because Running phase has higher priority by TPS threshold  and it overrides the taper according to determinePhase(). So there is no transition from cranking to running. There is cranking to idling transition. And therefore isIdling() should return true for CrankToIdleTaper as well.

Title: DRAFT IAC H Bridge Microstepping
Body: ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15104768/131740343-87c2b468-d5d2-40e0-b6e3-e98fc72347c3.png)    * A new setting "stepperDcInvertedPins" needed by RZ7899 H-bridge driver on Hellen boards. It's required because the outputs set to "low" only if both inputs set to "high":      ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15104768/131740627-facbbbfc-6b68-4a24-8421-4a75881597d8.png)    Without this option the PWM signal won't work on one channel if the second one is set to "low" (because "low+low" means "disabled" for that chip).    * Microstepping support for Half-Step  1/4-Step and 1/8-Step.    * Current limiting by setting min. and max. duty cycles for the H-bridge outputs. We don't measure the actual current  so we rely on this user-set values to save both the motor and the board from overheating.    * For example  this NEMA17 motor is rated 1.6A max  but direct 12V control draws >3A current  which is unacceptable:  Tested on a bench: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hIMrgqxTMaU

Title: last packet optimization
Body: The tcpip stack provides a flag that says "please defer sending  I have more data coming!".  We can set this flag on everything but the last bytes in a TS response to ensure that the packet isn't fragmented in either TCP or IP.  This improves performance and reduces overhead on both the ECU and PC side.

Title: Lua CAN RX
Body: 90% implements #3320    - Adds Lua function `listenCan(id)` to listen to a particular ID  - If `listenCan` has been called  the user-implemented function `onCanRx()` will be called whenever a new CAN frame is available.    The message passing mechanism is based on the one used already for logging.  Two lists are maintained: one of free buffers  and one of buffers queued for the Lua thread to process.    A future improvement could be to use a semaphore that immediately wakes the Lua thread if a new CAN message is available  instead of waiting for the normal tick function to run.    Tested by setting the CAN controller in loopback mode.

Title: Openblt
Body: This adds OpenBLT bootloader and tools as submodule to `firmware/ext/`  Also OpenBLT is build if `USE_OPENBLT` set to yes before calling `common_make.sh`  Boards specific OpenBLT code is expected at `firmware/config/boards/<board_name>/openblt/`. See OpenBLT `Target/Demo` or RusEFI's `boards/subaru_eg33` for example.  Initially OpenBLT can be flashed using DFU tool.  To flash main FW DFU util can be used.  Currently CRC check of main application is disabled in OpenBLT (for subaru board) and it is possible to load main application using DFU.  ```  $ time ./BootCommander -t=xcp_can -d=can0 /home/work/rusefi/rusefi/firmware/build/rusefi.srec   --------------------------------------------------------------------------  BootCommander version 1.04.02. Performs firmware updates on a micro-  controller based system that runs the OpenBLT bootloader.    Copyright (c) 2017 by Feaser  http://www.feaser.com  -------------------------------------------------------------------------  Processing command line parameters...[OK]  Detected firmware file: /home/work/rusefi/rusefi/firmware/build/rusefi.srec  Detected session protocol: XCP version 1.0  Using session protocol settings:    -> Timeout T1: 1000 ms    -> Timeout T3: 2000 ms    -> Timeout T4: 10000 ms    -> Timeout T5: 1000 ms    -> Timeout T6: 50 ms    -> Timeout T7: 2000 ms    -> Seed/Key file: None    -> Connection mode: 0  Detected transport layer: XCP on CAN  Using transport layer settings:    -> Device: can0 (channel 0)    -> Baudrate: 500000 bit/sec    -> Transmit CAN identifier: 667h    -> Receive CAN identifier: 7E1h    -> Use 29-bit CAN identifiers: No  Loading firmware data from file...[OK]    -> Number of segments: 3    -> Base memory address: 0x08008000    -> Total data size: 520908 bytes  Connecting to target bootloader...[OK]  Erasing 520 bytes starting at 0x08008000...[OK]    Erasing 424732 bytes starting at 0x08008210...[OK]    Erasing 95656 bytes starting at 0x0806fd30...[OK]    Programming 520 bytes starting at 0x08008000...[OK]    Programming 424732 bytes starting at 0x08008210...[OK]    Programming 95656 bytes starting at 0x0806fd30...[OK]    Finishing programming session...[OK]    real 1m35 129s  user 1m37 810s  ```

Title: Basic framework for high pressure fuel pump control
Body: DO NOT PULL THIS AS IS.  It is completely untested  not with the simulator  not with real hardware.  I was hoping it could be a spring board to discuss whether the approach is ok before I start writing actual unit tests.  Obviously there's a bit of chicken and egg here before testing on an actual running motor.    There are a lot of TODO that hopefully you can provide feedback on.    The compiles in the simulator.    The idea is to calculate the volume of fuel that needs to be added per lobe.  Then apply a simple PI controller on top of that to manage the pressure.    From the volume we calculate the # of degrees of pump action we need.    Then it's a matter of using VVT and other data to trigger the pump at the right time.

Title: Don t keep a separate MultiChannelStateSequence for the trigger emulator
Body: All it wants is to use the main trigger state  so don't bother copying it.  Instead  change  PwmConfig to take a const pointer to a Multi.*Sequence  then make all the users adapt.  Worse  fallout is that SimplePwm now has its own Multi.*Sequence  but PwmConfig is downgraded to a  pointer  so that's only a net +4 bytes.  And we can make the overhead of Multi.*Sequence much lower  using embedded arrays  which only the caller can do since it knows the maximum size... (for another  day...)    Also remove SimplePwm's 2nd copy of SingleChannelStateSequence.  It served no purpose.    Saves 1992 bytes of BSS and 24 bytes of RAM4 (latter probably due to SimplePwm change)

Title: Print BSS and RAM4 totals at the end of make

It's possible making these not static  would have helped  but link time optimization might have gotten rid of them too.    Instead  print BSS and RAM4 totals at the end using the java script.  If java is unable to run   don't error out the Makefile  just complain a little and move on.  Until the gcc_map_reader  actually works with RAM4  we print it manually.

Title: correctly compute engine revolution number
Body: This change helps the engine potentially start one cycle sooner  especially when using a crank-primary trigger.    Note how all the tests had to be adjusted to sync/measure RPM one cycle quicker than before!    tl;dr by starting the revolution counter at 0  `triggerIndexForListeners` is guaranteed to be zero at the very first sync point  so we can start everything the first time  instead of some number of sync points later.

Title: Drop SingleChannelStateSequence in favor of MultiChannelStateSequenceWithData
Body: Most all the users were Multi* anyways  so just improve that:  1. Allow up to 8 waveforms to share one byte per timestamp.  It could be better but this is simple     and gets most of the benefit.  2. Use a wrapper structure to handle reserving space for the arrays.  Makes the interface simpler     and more rigid.  Also saves 4 bytes per Multi*.  Downside is access is now via -> and *      not . and (nothing).    Saves 224 bytes of BSS  1832 bytes of RAM4/CCM  824 bytes of TEXT (yay? but unexpected...)  and  costs 26 bytes of RODATA (more yay?)

Title: ui config for fuel ign trim tables
Body: Adds a 4x4 trim to adjust fuel % and ignition degrees +/-  for every cylinder.   Since they share axes (all fuel trims share  all ign trims share)  it only uses 416 bytes of config space.    Since this is already an incompatible change requiring a change to `FLASH_DATA_VERSION`  this PR also:    - converts table axes to uint16_t (rpm  load where safe to do so) instead of using float #3045   - removes some unused config spacers  leaving 400 bytes available at the end of `engine_confguration_s` for added parameters.    Between these three changes  nets 1356 bytes of config (and therefore RAM) savings.

Title: Autoscale all the things
Body: Autoscale tables:  - VE  - injection phase  - ignition timing  - ignition IAT correction  - Boost tables  - pedal map    Saves a total of 2048 bytes of config space (!)  for a total of only 12992 bytes if we ignore the 8k of lua script.    depends on #3712

Title: fix dual CAN init update UI
Body: - Fixes broken H7 from dual CAN (but doesn't make CAN work on the H7).  - Corrects init sequence when using different baud rate on both devices  and when "logical CAN device 1" may be CAND2  not CAND1.  - Only initialize CAN read for devices that are configured  - Adjust UI to show one section for CAN data settings  and one section per CAN hardware (pins  bitrate)    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/147376593-154604f3-31c2-4697-b497-2a961ee4fca1.png)

Title: improved noFiringUntilVvtSync logic
Body: - Helps 36-1 swapped NB2 start faster  - Prevents wrong ignition/injection on other symmetrical crank vehicles (nissan  mostly)  - Reset trigger states (including vvt) when engine stops  - Minor tweak to NB crank sync condition    kind of #3015 related  very #3721 related

Title: remove vvtSyncTimeNt
Body: - Remove vvtSyncTimeNt  just check whether it's synchronized!  - Start decoding VVT as soon as the primary trigger is synchronized  don't wait for RPM information.  This improves time-to-first-fire on our checked in NB2 real world log test by 0.52 second  from 1.8 to 1.3 seconds from the start of cranking. Different initial conditions (where the engine happened to stop) may have even greater improvement.    #3721 and very #3015

Title: extract isSyncPoint function
Body: Extract isSyncPoint as its own function.  Prep for some custom decode logic to solve problems with NB2 trigger sync during cranking.    progress on #3721    Slightly improves performance as we can bail out (`return false;`) as soon as we find a gap that doesn't match.

Title: adjustment to 3722
Body: Using getShaftSynchronized doesn't work for non-decoder VVT modes  like "first half rising"  "vtwin map"  etc. Perhaps the best thing is to wait for the thing we KNOW we're waiting for  an adjustment of crank phase from the VVT system  so that's what this PR waits for.

Title: Nb2 crank sync special case
Body: Implement a special case of isSyncPoint for the NB Miata's crank trigger.  The NB crank trigger has some properties (described in the comment in code) that make it sort of annoying to sync when the engine accelerates rapidly (like during cranking!). This necessitated a sort of adaptive approach where we loosen the absolute requirements on the gap ratios  and rely on comparison between the current and previous gaps to find the sync point.    big progress on #3721  big progress on #3015

Title: GDI HPFP Set HPFP current timing params on MC33816
Body: obviously completely untested.  Please test!  I would use a spare injector or pump that you don't care about and test with an oscilloscope.  Yes I think you can use an injector since all you really need is something to sink 12V at various current levels.  Start by testing on a spare high impedance port injector since you know it'll never sink too much current while you make sure "on/off" works.    I would start with something like peak=5A  hold=3A  hold_off=10us  and hold_tot=10ms.
